Here are both approaches for MAUI Shell navigation with `IQueryAttributable`.

**1. Navigate with a simple string ID:**

```csharp
// ProductListPage.xaml.cs or ViewModel
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"ProductDetailsPage?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

**2. Navigate with the full object:**

```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("ProductDetailsPage", navParams);
}
```

> The single-parameter overload serializes values into the URL query string (strings/primitives only). The `Dictionary<string, object>` overload can pass complex objects.

**Receiving both on the ViewModel:**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1 â€“ simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            _productId = idObj.ToString();
            // Load product from service using _productId
        }

        // Approach 2 â€“ full object
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var prodObj) && prodObj is Product p)
        {
            _product = p;
            _productId = p.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

**Route registration (MauiProgram or AppShell):**

```csharp
Routing.RegisterRoute("ProductDetailsPage", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**Key points:**
- `ApplyQueryAttributes` is called automatically by Shell when the page resolves its `BindingContext` to a VM that implements `IQueryAttributable`.
- String params arrive as `string`; object params arrive as their original type â€” always type-check with `is`.
- Register the VM in DI so the page receives it via constructor injection; Shell will call `ApplyQueryAttributes` on it.
